Next week, the Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu will discuss the law on the provision of psychiatric care again.
Psychiatrists are the only specialists whose access requires parental consent for children under the age of eighteen.
Specialists involved in the committee's work have repeatedly highlighted the need to change the law.
Ave H asked why the amendment has stalled in the Riigikogu.
The gap in the law does not allow young people under the age of eighteen to seek psychiatric help without parental permission.
Although the authorities have repeatedly confirmed the need to change the law, young people continue to be left without help every month.
Young people should have the opportunity to seek help for themselves, regardless of what their family members think about it. The mistrust towards seeking help for mental health problems has not disappeared from all families.
The current law is largely based on the assumption that all children have supportive parents, a functioning family that can support their child and make decisions for them. Unfortunately, in my practical work, I see that this situation is different. Not all parents know how or, for some reason, do not want to deal with their child's problems. If they lack the necessary skills themselves, if they need help themselves, or if they are even the cause of their child's problems.
The topic has been discussed six times in the Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu. Various aspects of the problem have been explained by experts in the field, representatives of thirty-six organizations, who have also signed a joint appeal justifying the importance of the legislative amendment.

A year and a half has passed since the Chancellor of Justice drew the country's attention to the fact that this small legislative amendment would be fair and necessary for young people.

Today, we find ourselves in a situation where the Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu has been processing this issue for almost a year, including receiving support for this small legislative amendment from the Ministry of Education, Ministry of Justice, Ministry of Social Affairs, very loudly, including the Prime Minister and the Minister of Social Affairs. And yet, we are still processing it and cannot reach a conclusion.

What initially seemed like a small and simple legislative amendment has grown into a fundamental opposition. Urmas Espenberg, a member of the Social Affairs Committee from EKRE, says that theoretically they agree that young people should be able to see a psychiatrist without parental consent in exceptional cases. However, no agreement is reached in practice. According to Espenberg, two exceptional cases in which a young person could seek help from a psychiatrist without a parent present are the absence of a guardian or domestic violence.

I certainly do not agree that everyone will start going to psychiatrists as they please, so that every random child goes for counseling with a psychologist first, and then the psychologist decides what to do next.

What do opponents of the legislative amendments fear? Do they not trust young people or do they not trust experts in the field, namely psychiatrists?

Espenberg cites the need to collaborate with families, the fear that strong medications will be prescribed to young people, as well as the fear that mental health issues will become a trend or that young people will sell prescribed medications on the black market as the main reasons for opposition.

Young people are prone to trying all sorts of things, and when the word gets out that everyone can now go, then the talk about antidepressants starts, and maybe they will start selling them to each other.

A psychiatrist dispels the fears of opponents of the legislative amendments, as it is the doctor's task and competence to assess the patient's condition and act accordingly.

It is always the doctor's wisdom to see through these situations, to see the actual motives behind them, and how the use of medication is, meaning that there are rules in place that, if followed, prevent most of these problems.

Both medical professionals and youth workers consider the problem to be serious and in need of action.
I reached out to thirteen youth workers from four different organizations, and one-third of them have actually encountered situations where a child needed psychiatric help but it was not sought due to the parent's response.

I also asked them for stories, and these stories are, to put it mildly, frightening at times. Two of these stories even reached attempted suicides, fortunately unsuccessful, and one is an ongoing process where the child is afraid to contact their parents because their parents strongly believe that mental health issues are something only for the insane or the deeply religious.

Urmas Espemberg suggests a solution that some other adult who interacts with young people could issue a referral or permission to a psychiatrist.

In practice, this means that we have all kinds of networks, such as the youth and child protection network, the police, where certain cases are registered, and they can immediately make a referral there. There are also school psychologists available to whom one can turn. There are many possibilities, and there are many psychologists in Estonia, but they are all relatively underutilized, so we should think about how to solve these issues instead of blaming each other.

Each additional step increases bureaucracy and requires additional resources. Currently, there is a problem even fulfilling the existing requirements. Only thirty-nine percent of Estonian schools have a psychologist, which means that over half of the schools have to manage without one.

Where they are present, they are very capable, and where they are absent, there is a great shortage of them.

What happens when a person does not receive help in time?

In the case of mental disorders, one of the most common being depression, there is a high risk that it becomes chronic. But before it becomes chronic, it ruins your quality of life. A young person is unable to learn, unable to communicate, unable to fulfill themselves in life, and they disrupt everyday life. For example, they sit at home in front of the computer, no longer interested in sausage, but lying down there, among other things.

The number of people infected with the coronavirus exceeded two hundred on several days this week, and Minister of Social Affairs Tanel Kiik said on Friday that due to the spread of the coronavirus, Estonia is heading towards a health crisis.

Hanneli Rudi investigated how the virus is currently spreading.

Two hundred and eight, one hundred and thirty-one, two hundred and forty-one. These are not winning points in some dart game, but the numbers of people infected with the coronavirus this week, somewhat sad records.
However, Estonia stood out in mid-October in Europe for its exceptionally low infection rates. Now, in Tallinn and Harju County, the source of infection cannot be determined for every second patient, indicating that the disease has started to spread covertly. It may have been predictable, but well, COVID-19 is such a virus that tends to grow not as a steady spread, but rather in sudden outbreaks. However, it doesn't necessarily mean that things have gotten out of hand. I wouldn't say that at the moment. The growth rate is certainly the highest in the east, and it is unlikely that we can calmly handle it until spring with this growth rate. 

According to Mario Kadastik, the creator of COVID-19 models, such rapid growth in infections is expected because the reproduction number (R), which indicates how many people one infected person passes the virus to, has been between 1.2 and 1.4 in the past couple of weeks. By Saturday, this number had risen to 1.5, which means that two infected individuals transmit the infection to three others. Even if the reproduction number does not increase, it would still pose a serious threat to the Estonian healthcare system. In that case, hospitals would be filled with COVID-19 patients by the end of the year. 

While there has been much discussion about whether there are enough ventilators for COVID-19 patients, Kadastik says that the entire healthcare system will actually face a serious crisis. If the system completely collapses, as it has in some parts of the world where hospitals are filled only with COVID-19 patients, then the problem arises that we can no longer treat other conditions that are very treatable. COVID-19 departments also require significantly more staff, and therefore it is not possible to endlessly create more beds there. Kadastik suggests making an effort to bring the situation under control before the critical limit is reached. Based on the current numbers, he believes that we are still in the early phase of a large wave, rather than experiencing the spread of the disease in waves. It will continue with small fluctuations until the Health Board manages to trace most of the contacts. 

Well, we have been on the edge for a long time, and our dedicated inspectors from the Northern Regional Department are doing their best. Of course, the involvement of the speech robot has been very helpful. The speech robot does provide instructions to close contacts, but experience has shown that it is not enough, as people often do not understand the robot's message. Therefore, the COVID-19 detectives working in Tallinn have received assistance from about ten people who make phone calls to individuals. Detectives from other regions have also come to help.
Can there be a situation where you simply raise your hands and give up on seeking close contacts, or is this scenario completely ruled out?
This scenario is completely possible if we cannot keep the spread of the disease under control, right? And, it is very important right now that we all behave correctly, because right now everything is in our hands.
If the strength of the corona detectives weakens, according to Kadastik, there will be no escape from general restrictions.
In any exponential growth, the longer the growth lasts, the harder it is to eliminate the situation, so the sooner we get on top of it, the easier we can get rid of it.
Kadastik recommends avoiding face-to-face communication as much as possible, keeping a distance from strangers, and if that is not possible, then using a mask.
According to the scientist, it is worth remembering that the result of today's actions or restrictions will affect the corona statistics only two to four weeks later.
The scientific council advising the government has already presented its recommendations for restrictions.
Instead of restoring the rule of two plus two, they simply recommended a two-meter distance requirement.
Regarding couples or, well, when it comes to closing nightlife, we did recommend or, well, minimizing it, but no one is currently prohibiting anyone from wearing a mask indoors, so please people, wear a mask, does Jüri Ratas really have to tell you that?
Now let's see how many of us one person's infection can affect.
The Health Board described to us an actual virus outbreak where there were an exceptionally large number of close contacts.
Five hundred people ended up in isolation, many of whom had to interrupt their work for two weeks.
The focus of the case is the father, as the virus traveled to Estonia with the father of the family from abroad.
The returning father infected his wife, son, son's partner, two daughters, and daughter's child.
The infected mother worked in a care facility where she came into contact with ninety-five people.
Her close contacts were tested twice, none of them got sick.
One colleague of the son, who worked in a large collective, got infected and three hundred and sixty-five close contacts were put under surveillance, none of them got sick.
This infected colleague brought the infection home and five people in his household got infected.
The son's partner worked in a restaurant, which was closed, and fourteen contacts were sent into isolation, fortunately, no one got sick.
The daughter, who attends school, had twenty-one close contacts, all of whom were sent into home isolation, and no one got sick.
The daughter's kindergarten was closed and fourteen close contacts were under surveillance, no one got sick.
In addition, eighteen acquaintances of the families were in isolation at that time, and they also did not get sick. As a result of this outbreak, thirteen people were infected and five hundred twenty-seven people were in two-week isolation and under the supervision of the Health Board.
