Ott Nool talks about the weather for the new week.
Good evening, it is gradually getting colder outside, as tomorrow a high-pressure system will dominate the Baltic Sea region, with its center located over Poland.
And along the edge of the high-pressure system, colder air from the northwest will reach the Baltic States and Finland, causing temperatures to drop below freezing overnight in inland areas and creating a risk of slippery roads.
During the day tomorrow, a weak low-pressure trough will also take advantage of the movement along the edge of this high-pressure system, coming from Finland and passing over Estonia towards the southeast, bringing light precipitation to Northern Estonia.
On Tuesday, the low-pressure trough will move away towards Russia and the high-pressure system will cover the Baltic Sea region, although there will still be moisture in the area and, as is typical in autumn, a high-pressure system does not always mean sunny weather.
During the night, cloudiness will vary and there will be occasional rain in coastal areas, with a west-northwest wind blowing at two to seven meters per second, gusting up to eleven meters per second along the coast.
The air temperature will range from minus two to plus three degrees Celsius, occasionally reaching five degrees along the coast.
The morning will be mostly cloudy, but clearer skies can be expected in Southeast Estonia.
Rain will mainly occur in coastal areas, with a southwest to west wind blowing at three to eight meters per second, gusting up to twelve meters per second.
On the northern coast, there will also be a northwest wind blowing at seven to twelve meters per second, gusting up to sixteen meters per second.
In some places, the temperature may drop below freezing in the morning, with temperatures ranging from minus one to plus five degrees Celsius, up to eight degrees along the coast.
During the day, there will be occasional light rain and the chance of precipitation will decrease in the afternoon.
A southwest to west wind will blow at five to eleven meters per second, gusting up to fifteen meters per second, and temperatures will range from five to ten degrees Celsius.
Tuesday promises to be clearer, but Wednesday will become slightly more rainy.
Similarly, the rest of the week will continue.
The air temperature will be lower compared to the previous week, ranging from an average of zero to four degrees Celsius at night and five to seven degrees during the day.
The days are getting shorter and the coolness is slowly creeping in. Have a nice evening.
